request.description:
StartFragment

In the context of X.509 client certificates, the CN (Common Name) attribute is a part of the Distinguished Name (DN) that identifies the subject of the certificate. The CN contains the name of the entity that the certificate belongs to, such as a person, an organization, or a service. In the context of the quote provided, the CN value from the DN is used as the username to look up group membership in authentication backends. Essentially, it serves as the identifier for the user or entity associated with the certificate.

EndFragment

response.name: get Federation Config

request.description:
returns the group that are configured for a certain CA.  

the ID of the CA is visible in the Federate Certificate Authority Groups Page

EndFragment
Add a federated group to the certs. Notice that the group is NOT created in the group management, nor it's check if the group exists

returns the unique ID of the TAK server
returns all clients connected
Returns all the clients ever connected (with time parameters
returns a list of groupd available to the user
returns "/Marti/security/index.html" where you can see the security configuration. Not sure why this is exposed no anon group

returns all the users and the group they are subscribed to.  

StartFragment

In the context of X.509 client certificates, the CN (Common Name) attribute is a part of the Distinguished Name (DN) that identifies the subject of the certificate. The CN contains the name of the entity that the certificate belongs to, such as a person, an organization, or a service. In the context of the quote provided, the CN value from the DN is used as the username to look up group membership in authentication backends. Essentially, it serves as the identifier for the user or entity associated with the certificate.

EndFragment

request.description: return a HTML (!) message containing the # of completed/containing tasks

item.description:
StartFragment

The Execution Checklist (ExCheck) Plug-in allows users to monitor and update the status of a shared checklist that is hosted on a TAK Server. Each checklist is an instance of a template that defines tasks to be completed.

EndFragment

item.name: missions

request.description: returns the ID of All subscribed clients
set th mission keywords, this will overwrite the previous ones

Invite a certain type to the mission.

the enum type includes:

StartFragment

clientUid, callsign, username, group, team

defined in:

takserver-core/takserver-war/src/main/java/com/bbn/marti/sync/model/MissionInvitation.java

EndFragment
invite a list of usrs, unclear how the contacts array is structured

remove mission content by a single hash or uid

Either hash or uid must be specified, not both

Add Enterprise Sync resources (files) that can be referenced by hash and / or uid.

`{   "hashes" :`

`[ "", "" ],   "uids" :   ["", "" ]   }`

EndFragment
post a binary file to the mission

item.name: Resource - Mission logs

request.description:
Add a log entry to the server.

- content : The text of the log entry
- creatorUid : Client UID
- entryUid : UID of associated CoT track
- missionNames : Missions to associate with this log entry
- text of the log entry, not a server-side timestamp)
    

The response is a reflection of the incoming request - with the significant addition of the **id**, which is a pseudo-random 128-bit identifier assigned by the server at entry creation time, and "servertime" - the server-side timestamp at creation time

query.description: time interval - number of seconds in the the past, until now
start of time interval. Takes precedence over "secago" if specified.

item.description:
The Data Sync / Mission API provides the capability in TAK Server for clients, such as ATAK,  
to share collections of information which are tracked as part of missions. Once a mission has  
been created by a client, it immediately becomes available to other clients (Assuming they have the plugin).

A substantial portion the API and related functions have been developed in order to provide clients with the ability to add and remove relevant mission content, determine what changes to missions have been done by other clients, and then request updates for only what each client requires. In this way, each client can always maintain a consistent local view of missions and their contents, which conserving resources such as local storage and network bandwidth.

There are several types of content that can be associated with a mission:

- **CoT tracks**: CoT tracks are referenced by their UID, so that any information that can be  
    represented in a mission. Once CoT UIDs have been added to a mission, the server can then  
    provide the client with the latest CoT event associated with each UID
- **enterprise sync resources**: Files can be uploaded to TAK Server through the Enterprise Sync API. The adds generality such that any type of file that is useful from a client perspective can be added to a mission.  
    Common files types include GRGs, images, and KML (Keyhole markup language) files. These  
    resources are referenced by calculating a deterministic hash for each file, based on the binary  
    contents of the file. Once the association has been made between a mission and a file, the  
    file contents of the mission can be searched by parameters including time interval and  
    geographic location.
- **Check Lists:** requires the ExChecks plugin installed. Allow the collaborative execution of a series of tasks
- **mission logs**: Mission Logs are a series of free-form text entries that can be viewed individually or as a complete log.
    

In addition to CoT tracks and files, each mission can also contain a "Mission Log" (also referred to as a "Recce Log"). Mission logs are composed of individual log entries, which clients post to the server. Once a log entry has been added, it immediately becomes available as part of the mission log, in a similar fashion to enterprise sync resources and CoT tracks. CoT UIDs and file resources can also be associated with individual log entries,  
just as they can be associated with missions. Log entries may also be updated and deleted.  
Similarly, tracks and files can also be removed from the mission. Every change to the state of a mission, including the creation or deletion of the mission itself, is tracked by TAK Server. Based on this information, the server can generate a change log detailing each change to the mission over time. This log can be filtered based on an arbitrary time interval.  
Clients may subscribe to one or more missions. Once a client has subscribed to a mission, the server will send it a CoT message informing the client of each change. Based on this notification, the client can then request a change log for an appropriate time range.
